process_flag(max_heap_size, max_heap_size())

.fi

.PP
This flag sets the maximum heap size for the calling process. If \fIMaxHeapSize\fR is an integer, the system default values for \fIkill\fR and \fIerror_logger\fR are used.

.PP
For details on how the heap grows, see Sizing the heap in the ERTS internal documentation.

size
.RS 2
The maximum size in words of the process. If set to zero, the heap size limit is disabled. 
\fIbadarg\fR is be thrown if the value is smaller than \fImin_heap_size\fR. The size check is only done when a garbage collection is triggered.
.PP
\fIsize\fR is the entire heap of the process when garbage collection is triggered. This includes all generational heaps, the process stack, any messages that are considered to be part of the heap, and any extra memory that the garbage collector needs during collection.

.PP
\fIsize\fR is the same as can be retrieved using \fIerlang:process_info(Pid, total_heap_size)\fR, or by adding \fIheap_block_size\fR, \fIold_heap_block_size\fR and \fImbuf_size\fR from \fIerlang:process_info(Pid, garbage_collection_info)\fR.


.RE

kill
.RS 2
When set to 
\fItrue\fR, the runtime system sends an untrappable exit signal with reason \fIkill\fR to the process if the maximum heap size is reached. The garbage collection that triggered the \fIkill\fR is not completed, instead the process exits as soon as possible. When set to \fIfalse\fR, no exit signal is sent to the process, instead it continues executing.
.PP
If \fIkill\fR is not defined in the map, the system default will be used. The default system default is \fItrue\fR. It can be changed by either option +hmaxk in erl, or \fIerlang:system_flag(max_heap_size, MaxHeapSize)\fR.


.RE

error_logger
.RS 2
When set to 
\fItrue\fR, the runtime system logs an error event via \fIlogger\fR, containing details about the process when the maximum heap size is reached. One log event is sent each time the limit is reached.
.PP
If \fIerror_logger\fR is not defined in the map, the system default is used. The default system default is \fItrue\fR. It can be changed by either the option +hmaxel int erl, or \fIerlang:system_flag(max_heap_size, MaxHeapSize)\fR.


.RE

include_shared_binaries
.RS 2
When set to 
\fItrue\fR, off-heap binaries are included in the total sum compared against the \fIsize\fR limit. Off-heap binaries are typically larger binaries that may be shared between processes. The size of a shared binary is included by all processes that are referring it. Also, the entire size of a large binary may be included even if only a smaller part of it is referred by the process.
.PP
If \fIinclude_shared_binaries\fR is not defined in the map, the system default is used. The default system default is \fIfalse\fR. It can be changed by either the option +hmaxib in erl, or \fIerlang:system_flag(max_heap_size, MaxHeapSize)\fR.


.RE

.PP
The heap size of a process is quite hard to predict, especially the amount of memory that is used during the garbage collection. When contemplating using this option, it is recommended to first run it in production with \fIkill\fR set to \fIfalse\fR and inspect the log events to see what the normal peak sizes of the processes in the system is and then tune the value accordingly.

.RE


