.RE
.B
\fBprocess_info(Pid, Item) -> InfoTuple | [] | undefined\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Pid :: pid(),\fR
\fB                          Item :: process_info_item(),\fR
\fB                          InfoTuple :: process_info_result_item();\fR
\fB                  (Pid, ItemList) -> InfoTupleList | [] | undefined\fR
\fB                      when\fR
\fB                          Pid :: pid(),\fR
\fB                          ItemList :: [Item],\fR
\fB                          Item :: process_info_item(),\fR
\fB                          InfoTupleList :: [InfoTuple],\fR
\fB                          InfoTuple :: process_info_result_item().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns information about the process identified by \fIPid\fR, as specified by \fIItem\fR or \fIItemList\fR. Returns \fIundefined\fR if the process is not alive.

.PP
If the process is alive and a single \fIItem\fR is specified, the returned value is the corresponding \fIInfoTuple\fR, unless \fIItem =:= registered_name\fR and the process has no registered name. In this case, \fI[]\fR is returned. This strange behavior is because of historical reasons, and is kept for backward compatibility.

.PP
If \fIItemList\fR is specified, the result is \fIInfoTupleList\fR. The \fIInfoTuple\fRs in \fIInfoTupleList\fR are included with the corresponding \fIItem\fRs in the same order as the \fIItem\fRs were included in \fIItemList\fR. Valid \fIItem\fRs can be included multiple times in \fIItemList\fR.

.PP
Getting process information follows the signal ordering guarantees described in the Processes Chapter in the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIf \fIregistered_name\fR is part of \fIItemList\fR and the process has no name registered, a \fI{registered_name, []}\fR, \fIInfoTuple\fR \fIwill\fR be included in the resulting \fIInfoTupleList\fR. This behavior is different when a single \fIItem =:= registered_name\fR is specified, and when \fIprocess_info/1\fR is used.


.PP
Valid \fIInfoTuple\fRs with corresponding \fIItem\fRs:

{async_dist, Enabled}
.RS 2
Current value of the 
\fIasync_dist\fR process flag.
.PP
Since: OTP 25.3


.RE

{backtrace, Bin}
.RS 2
Binary 
\fIBin\fR contains the same information as the output from \fIerlang:process_display(Pid, backtrace)\fR. Use \fIbinary_to_list/1\fR to obtain the string of characters from the binary.

.RE

{binary, BinInfo}
.RS 2

\fIBinInfo\fR is a list containing miscellaneous information about binaries on the heap of this process. This \fIInfoTuple\fR can be changed or removed without prior notice. In the current implementation \fIBinInfo\fR is a list of tuples. The tuples contain; \fIBinaryId\fR, \fIBinarySize\fR, \fIBinaryRefcCount\fR.
.PP
Depending on the value of the \fImessage_queue_data\fR process flag the message queue may be stored on the heap.


.RE

{catchlevel, CatchLevel}
.RS 2

\fICatchLevel\fR is the number of currently active catches in this process. This \fIInfoTuple\fR can be changed or removed without prior notice.

.RE

{current_function, {Module, Function, Arity} | undefined}
.RS 2

\fIModule\fR, \fIFunction\fR, \fIArity\fR is the current function call of the process. The value \fIundefined\fR can be returned if the process is currently executing native compiled code.

.RE

{current_location, {Module, Function, Arity, Location}}
.RS 2

\fIModule\fR, \fIFunction\fR, \fIArity\fR is the current function call of the process. \fILocation\fR is a list of two-tuples describing the location in the source code.

