.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIspawn_request(Node,erlang,apply,[Fun,[]],Options)\fR](\fIspawn_request/5\fR) or [\fIspawn_request(node(),Module,Function,Args,[])\fR depending on the arguments.

.PP
That is either:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
spawn request using the fun \fIFun\fR of arity zero as entry point

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
spawn request on the local node with no options.

.RE

.PP
This function will fail with a \fIbadarg\fR exception if:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fINode\fR is not an atom.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIFun\fR is not a fun of arity zero.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIOptions\fR is not a proper list of terms.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBspawn_request(Node, Module, Function, Args) -> ReqId\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Node :: node(),\fR
\fB                           Module :: module(),\fR
\fB                           Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                           Args :: [term()],\fR
\fB                           ReqId :: reference();\fR
\fB                   (Module, Function, Args, Options) -> ReqId\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Module :: module(),\fR
\fB                           Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                           Args :: [term()],\fR
\fB                           Option ::\fR
\fB                               {reply_tag, ReplyTag} |\fR
\fB                               {reply, Reply} |\fR
\fB                               spawn_opt_option(),\fR
\fB                           ReplyTag :: term(),\fR
\fB                           Reply :: yes | no | error_only | success_only,\fR
\fB                           Options :: [Option],\fR
\fB                           ReqId :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIspawn_request(Node,Module,Function,Args,[])\fR or \fIspawn_request(node(),Module,Function,Args,Options)\fR depending on the arguments.

.PP
That is either:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
spawn request with no options.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
spawn request on the local node.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBspawn_request(Node, Module, Function, Args, Options) -> ReqId\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Node :: node(),\fR
\fB                           Module :: module(),\fR
\fB                           Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                           Args :: [term()],\fR
\fB                           Options :: [Option],\fR
\fB                           Option ::\fR
\fB                               monitor |\fR
\fB                               {monitor, [monitor_option()]} |\fR
\fB                               link |\fR
\fB                               {reply_tag, ReplyTag} |\fR
\fB                               {reply, Reply} |\fR
\fB                               OtherOption,\fR
\fB                           ReplyTag :: term(),\fR
\fB                           Reply :: yes | no | error_only | success_only,\fR
\fB                           OtherOption :: term(),\fR
\fB                           ReqId :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Asynchronously send a spawn request. Returns a request identifier \fIReqId\fR.

.PP
If the spawn operation succeeds, a new process is created on the node identified by \fINode\fR. When a spawn operation succeeds, the caller will by default be sent a message of the form \fI{ReplyTag, ReqId, ok, Pid}\fR where \fIPid\fR is the process identifier of the newly created process. Such a message is referred to as a \fIsuccess message\fR below in the text. \fIReplyTag\fR is by default the atom \fIspawn_reply\fR unless modified by the \fI{reply_tag, ReplyTag}\fR option. The new process is started by the application of \fIModule:Function\fR to \fIArgs\fR.

.PP
The spawn operation fails either if creation of a new process failed or if the spawn operation was interrupted by a connection failure. When a spawn operation fails, the caller will by default be sent a message on the form \fI{ReplyTag, ReqId, error, Reason}\fR where \fIReason\fR is the error reason. Such a message is referred to as an \fIerror message\fR below in the text. Currently the following spawn error \fIReason\fRs are defined, but other reasons can appear at any time without prior notice:

badopt
.RS 2
An invalid 
\fIOption\fR was passed as argument. Note that different runtime systems may support different options.

.RE

notsup
.RS 2
The node identified by 
\fINode\fR does not support spawn operations issued by \fIspawn_request()\fR.

.RE

noconnection
.RS 2
Failure to set up a connection to the node identified by 
\fINode\fR or the connection to that node was lost during the spawn operation. In the case the connection was lost, a process may or may not have been created.

.RE

system_limit
.RS 2
Could not create a new process due to that some system limit was reached. Typically the process table was full.


.RE

.PP
Valid \fIOption\fRs:

monitor
.RS 2
In the absence of spawn operation failures, atomically sets up a monitor to the newly created process. That is, as if the calling process had called 
\fImonitor(process, Pid)\fR where \fIPid\fR is the process identifier of the newly created process. The \fIReqId\fR returned by \fIspawn_request()\fR is also used as monitor reference as if it was returned from \fImonitor(process, Pid)\fR.
.PP
The monitor will not be activated for the calling process until the spawn operation has succeeded. The monitor can not be demonitored before the operation has succeeded. A \fI'DOWN'\fR message for the corresponding monitor is guaranteed not to be delivered before a \fIsuccess message\fR that corresponds to the spawn operation. If the spawn operation fails, no \fI'DOWN'\fR message will be delivered.

.PP
If the connection between the nodes involved in the spawn operation is lost during the spawn operation, the spawn operation will fail with an error reason of \fInoconnection\fR. A new process may or may not have been created.


.RE

{monitor, MonitorOpts}
.RS 2
In the absence of spawn operation failures, atomically sets up a monitor to the newly created process. That is, as if the calling process had called 
\fImonitor(process, Pid, MonitorOpts)\fR where \fIPid\fR is the process identifier of the newly created process. See the \fImonitor\fR option above for more information.
.PP
Note that the monitor will not be activated for the calling process until the spawn operation has succeeded. For example, in the case that an alias is created using the monitor option, the alias will not be active until the monitor is activated.


.RE

link
.RS 2
In absence of spawn operation failures, atomically sets up a link between the calling process and the newly created process. That is, as if the calling process had called 
\fIlink(Pid)\fR where \fIPid\fR is the process identifier of the newly created process.
.PP
The link will not be activated for the calling process until the spawn operation has succeeded. The link can not be removed before the operation has succeeded. An exit signal due to the link is guaranteed not to be delivered before a \fIsuccess message\fR that corresponds to the spawn operation. If the spawn operation fails, no exit signal due to the link will be delivered to the caller of \fIspawn_request()\fR.

.PP
If the connection between the nodes involved in the spawn operation is lost during the spawn operation, the spawn operation will fail with an error reason of \fInoconnection\fR. A new process may or may not have been created. If it has been created, it will be delivered an exit signal with an exit reason of \fInoconnection\fR.


.RE

{reply, Reply}
.RS 2
Valid 
\fIReply\fR values:
yes
.RS 2
A spawn reply message will be sent to the caller regardless of whether the operation succeeds or not. If the call to 
\fIspawn_request()\fR returns without raising an exception and the \fIreply\fR option is set to \fIyes\fR, the caller is guaranteed to be delivered either a \fIsuccess message\fR or an \fIerror message\fR. The \fIreply\fR option is by default set to \fIyes\fR.

.RE

no
.RS 2
No spawn reply message will be sent to the caller when the spawn operation completes. This regardless of whether the operation succeeds or not.


.RE

error_only
.RS 2
No spawn reply message will be sent to the caller if the spawn operation succeeds, but an 
\fIerror message\fR will be sent to the caller if the operation fails.

.RE

success_only
.RS 2
No spawn reply message will be sent to the caller if the spawn operation fails, but a 
\fIsuccess message\fR will be sent to the caller if the operation succeeds.

.RE


.RE

{reply_tag, ReplyTag}
.RS 2
Sets the reply tag to 
\fIReplyTag\fR in the reply message. That is, in the \fIsuccess\fR or \fIerror\fR message that is sent to the caller due to the spawn operation. The default reply tag is the atom \fIspawn_reply\fR.

.RE

OtherOption
.RS 2
Other valid options depends on what options are supported by the node identified by 
\fINode\fR. A description of other valid \fIOption\fRs for the local node of current OTP version can be found in the documentation of \fIspawn_opt/4\fR.

.RE

.PP
If a spawn reply message is delivered, it is guaranteed to be delivered before any other signals from the newly spawned process are delivered to the process issuing the spawn request.

.PP
This function will fail with a \fIbadarg\fR exception if:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fINode\fR is not an atom.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIModule\fR is not an atom.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIFunction\fR is not an atom.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIArgs\fR is not a proper list of terms.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIOptions\fR is not a proper list of terms.

.RE

.PP
Note that not all individual \fIOption\fRs are checked when the spawn request is sent. Some \fIOption\fRs can only be checked on reception of the request. Therefore an invalid option does \fInot\fR cause a \fIbadarg\fR exception, but will cause the spawn operation to fail with an error reason of \fIbadopt\fR.

.PP
A spawn request can be abandoned by calling \fIspawn_request_abandon/1\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRFor some important information about distributed signals, see the \fIBlocking Signaling Over Distribution\fR section in the \fIProcesses\fR chapter of the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR.



.RE
.B
\fBspawn_request_abandon(ReqId :: reference()) -> boolean().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Abandon a previously issued spawn request. \fIReqId\fR corresponds to a request identifier previously returned by \fIspawn_request()\fR in a call from current process. That is, only the process that has made the request can abandon the request.

.PP
A spawn request can only be successfully abandoned until the spawn request has completed. When a spawn request has been successfully abandoned, the caller will not be effected by future direct effects of the spawn request itself. For example, it will not receive a spawn reply message. The request is however not withdrawn, so a new process may or may not be created due to the request. If a new process is created after the spawn request was abandoned, no monitors nor links will be set up to the caller of \fIspawn_request_abandon/1\fR due to the spawn request. If the spawn request included the \fIlink\fR option, the process created due to this request will be sent an exit signal from its parent with the exit reason \fIabandoned\fR when it is detected that the spawn operation has succeeded.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRA process created due to a spawn request that has been abandoned may communicate with its parent as any other process. It is \fIonly\fR the direct effects on the parent of the actual spawn request, that will be canceled by abandoning a spawn request.


.PP
Return values:

true
.RS 2
The spawn request was successfully abandoned.


.RE

false
.RS 2
No spawn request was abandoned. The 
\fIReqId\fR request identifier did not correspond to an outstanding spawn request issued by the calling process. The reason for this is either:

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIReqId\fR corresponds to a spawn request previoulsy made by the calling process. The spawn operation has completed and a spawn reply has already been delivered to the calling process unless the spawn reply was disabled in the request.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIReqId\fR does not correspond to a spawn request that has been made by the calling process.

.RE


.RE

.PP
This function fail with a \fIbadarg\fR exception if \fIReqId\fR is not a reference.


.RE
.B
\fBsplit_binary(Bin, Pos) -> {binary(), binary()}\fR
\fB                      when Bin :: binary(), Pos :: non_neg_integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns a tuple containing the binaries that are the result of splitting \fIBin\fR into two parts at position \fIPos\fR.

.PP
This operation is non-destructive. After the operation, there are three binaries altogether.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> B = list_to_binary("0123456789").
<<"0123456789">>
2> byte_size(B).
10
3> {B1, B2} = split_binary(B, 3).
{<<"012">>,<<"3456789">>}
4> byte_size(B1).
3
5> byte_size(B2).
7

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBstart_timer(Time, Dest, Msg, Options) -> TimerRef\fR
\fB                     when\fR
\fB                         Time :: integer(),\fR
\fB                         Dest :: pid() | atom(),\fR
\fB                         Msg :: term(),\fR
\fB                         Options :: [Option],\fR
\fB                         Abs :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                         Option :: {abs, Abs},\fR
\fB                         TimerRef :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Starts a timer. When the timer expires, the message \fI{timeout, TimerRef, Msg}\fR is sent to the process identified by \fIDest\fR.

.PP
\fIOption\fRs:

{abs, false}
.RS 2
This is the default. It means the 
\fITime\fR value is interpreted as a time in milliseconds \fIrelative\fR current Erlang monotonic time.

.RE

{abs, true}
.RS 2
Absolute 
\fITime\fR value. The \fITime\fR value is interpreted as an absolute Erlang monotonic time in milliseconds.

.RE

.PP
More \fIOption\fRs can be added in the future.

.PP
The absolute point in time, the timer is set to expire on, must be in the interval \fI \fR[erlang:convert_time_unit\fI(\fRerlang:system_info\fI(start_time), native, millisecond), \fRerlang:convert_time_unit\fI(\fRerlang:system_info\fI(end_time), native, millisecond) ]\fR. If a relative time is specified, the \fITime\fR value is not allowed to be negative.

.PP
If \fIDest\fR is a \fIpid/0\fR, it must be a \fIpid/0\fR of a process created on the current runtime system instance. This process has either terminated or not. If \fIDest\fR is an \fIatom/0\fR, it is interpreted as the name of a locally registered process. The process referred to by the name is looked up at the time of timer expiration. No error is returned if the name does not refer to a process.

.PP
If \fIDest\fR is a \fIpid/0\fR, the timer is automatically canceled if the process referred to by the \fIpid/0\fR is not alive, or if the process exits. This feature was introduced in ERTS 5.4.11. Notice that timers are not automatically canceled when \fIDest\fR is an \fIatom/0\fR.

.PP
See also \fIerlang:send_after/4\fR, \fIerlang:cancel_timer/2\fR, and \fIerlang:read_timer/2\fR.

.PP
For more information on timers in Erlang in general, see the \fITimers\fR section of the \fITime and Time Correction in Erlang\fR ERTS User's guide.

.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if the arguments do not satisfy the requirements specified here.


.RE
