.PP
For more detailed descriptions about the monitoring options, see \fItrace:system/3\fR.

.PP
Unlike \fItrace:system/3\fR, the arguments to \fIsystem_monitor/2\fR specify how all system monitoring should be set, not how it should be changed. This means only one process at a time (\fIMonitorPid\fR) can be the receiver of messages from system monitoring set with this function. Also, the way to clear a specific monitor option is to not include it in the list \fIOptions\fR. All system monitoring will, however, be cleared if the process identified by \fIMonitorPid\fR terminates.

.PP
There are no special option values (like zero) to clear an option. Some of the options have a unspecified minimum value. Lower values will be adjusted to the minimum value. For example, it is currently not possible to monitor all garbage collections with \fI{long_gc, 0}\fR.

.PP
Returns the previous system monitor settings just like \fIerlang:system_monitor/0\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIf a monitoring process gets so large that it itself starts to cause system monitor messages when garbage collecting, the messages enlarge the process message queue and probably make the problem worse. Keep the monitoring process neat and do not set the system monitor limits too tight.


.PP
Failures:

badarg
.RS 2
If 
\fIMonitorPid\fR does not exist.

.RE

badarg
.RS 2
If 
\fIMonitorPid\fR is not a local process.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBsystem_profile() -> ProfilerSettings\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            ProfilerSettings ::\fR
\fB                                undefined | {ProfilerPid, Options},\fR
\fB                            ProfilerPid :: pid() | port(),\fR
\fB                            Options :: [system_profile_option()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the current system profiling settings set by \fIerlang:system_profile/2\fR as \fI{ProfilerPid, Options}\fR, or \fIundefined\fR if there are no settings. The order of the options can be different from the one that was set.


.RE
.B
\fBsystem_profile(ProfilerPid, Options) -> ProfilerSettings\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            ProfilerPid :: pid() | port() | undefined,\fR
\fB                            Options :: [system_profile_option()],\fR
\fB                            ProfilerSettings ::\fR
\fB                                undefined |\fR
\fB                                {pid() | port(),\fR
\fB                                 [system_profile_option()]}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Sets system profiler options. \fIProfilerPid\fR is a local process identifier (pid) or port receiving profiling messages. The receiver is excluded from all profiling. The second argument is a list of profiling options:

exclusive
.RS 2
If a synchronous call to a port from a process is done, the calling process is considered not runnable during the call runtime to the port. The calling process is notified as 
\fIinactive\fR, and later \fIactive\fR when the port callback returns.

.RE

monotonic_timestamp
.RS 2
Time stamps in profile messages use Erlang monotonic time. The time stamp (Ts) has the same format and value as produced by 
\fIerlang:monotonic_time(nanosecond)\fR.

.RE

runnable_procs
.RS 2
If a process is put into or removed from the run queue, a message, 
\fI{profile, Pid, State, Mfa, Ts}\fR, is sent to \fIProfilerPid\fR. Running processes that are reinserted into the run queue after having been pre-empted do not trigger this message.

.RE

runnable_ports
.RS 2
If a port is put into or removed from the run queue, a message, 
\fI{profile, Port, State, 0, Ts}\fR, is sent to \fIProfilerPid\fR.

.RE

scheduler
.RS 2
If a scheduler is put to sleep or awoken, a message, 
\fI{profile, scheduler, Id, State, NoScheds, Ts}\fR, is sent to \fIProfilerPid\fR.

.RE

strict_monotonic_timestamp
.RS 2
Time stamps in profile messages consist of Erlang monotonic time and a monotonically increasing integer. The time stamp (Ts) has the same format and value as produced by 
\fI{erlang:monotonic_time(nanosecond), erlang:unique_integer([monotonic])}\fR.

.RE

timestamp
.RS 2
Time stamps in profile messages include a time stamp (Ts) that has the same form as returned by 
\fIerlang:now()\fR. This is also the default if no time stamp flag is specified. If \fIcpu_timestamp\fR has been enabled through \fItrace:process/4\fR, this also effects the time stamp produced in profiling messages when flag \fItimestamp\fR is enabled.

.RE

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fR\fIerlang:system_profile\fR behavior can change in a future release.



.RE
.B
\fBsystem_time() -> integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns current Erlang system time in \fInative\fR time unit.

.PP
Calling \fIerlang:system_time()\fR is equivalent to \fIerlang:monotonic_time()\fR\fI+\fR\fIerlang:time_offset()\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis time is \fInot\fR a monotonically increasing time in the general case. For more information, see the documentation of time warp modes in the User's Guide.



.RE
.B
\fBsystem_time(Unit) -> integer() when Unit :: time_unit().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns current Erlang system time converted into the \fIUnit\fR passed as argument.

.PP
Calling \fIerlang:system_time(Unit)\fR is equivalent to \fIerlang:convert_time_unit\fR\fI(\fR\fIerlang:system_time()\fR\fI, native, Unit)\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis time is \fInot\fR a monotonically increasing time in the general case. For more information, see the documentation of time warp modes in the User's Guide.



.RE
.B
\fBterm_to_binary(Term) -> ext_binary() when Term :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns a binary data object that is the result of encoding \fITerm\fR according to the Erlang external term format.

.PP
This can be used for various purposes, such as efficiently writing a term to a file or sending an Erlang term through a communication channel not supported by distributed Erlang.

.PP
See also \fIbinary_to_term/1\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThere is no guarantee that this function will always return the same encoded representation for the same term.


.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> Bin = term_to_binary(hello).
<<131,119,5,104,101,108,108,111>>
2> hello = binary_to_term(Bin).
hello

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBterm_to_binary(Term, Options) -> ext_binary()\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            Term :: term(),\fR
\fB                            Options ::\fR
\fB                                [compressed |\fR
\fB                                 {compressed, Level :: 0..9} |\fR
\fB                                 deterministic |\fR
\fB                                 {minor_version, Version :: 0..2} |\fR
\fB                                 local].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns a binary data object that is the result of encoding \fITerm\fR according to the Erlang external term format.

.PP
Supported options:

compressed
.RS 2
Compress the external term format. The compressed format is automatically recognized by 
\fIbinary_to_term/1\fR as from Erlang/OTP R7B.

.RE

{compressed, Level}
.RS 2
Compress the external term format to a given level. The compression level is specified by 
\fILevel\fR which is an integer in the range 0 to 9, where:
0
.RS 2
No compression is applied (equivalent to omitting the 
\fIcompressed\fR option).

.RE

1
.RS 2
Fastest compression but may not compress as well as the higher levels.


.RE

6
.RS 2
Default level when the 
\fIcompressed\fR option is provided.

.RE

9
.RS 2
Highest compression level, taking the longest time while attempting to produce the smallest result. However, depending on the input term, level 9 compression may not always produce a smaller result than level 1 compression.


.RE


.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fI{minor_version, Version}\fR\fR(Since R11B-4)  The option can be used to control some encoding details. Valid values for \fIVersion\fR are:

0
.RS 2
Floats are encoded using a textual representation.

.PP
Atoms that can be represented by a latin1 string are encoded using latin1 while only atoms that cannot be represented by latin1 are encoded using utf8.


.RE

1
.RS 2
Floats are encoded in a more space-efficient and exact way (namely in the 64-bit IEEE format, rather than converted to a textual representation). As from Erlang/OTP R11B-4, 
\fIbinary_to_term/1\fR can decode this representation.
.PP
Atoms that can be represented by a latin1 string are encoded using latin1 while only atoms that cannot be represented by latin1 are encoded using utf8.


.RE

2
.RS 2
This is as of Erlang/OTP 26.0 the 
\fIdefault\fR. Atoms are unconditionally encoded using utf8. Erlang/OTP systems as of R16B can decode this representation.

.RE

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIdeterministic\fR\fR(Since OTP 24.1)  This option can be used to ensure that, within the same major release of Erlang/OTP, the same encoded representation is returned for the same term. There is still no guarantee that the encoded representation remains the same between major releases of Erlang/OTP.

.PP
This option cannot be combined with the \fIlocal\fR option.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIlocal\fR \fR(Since OTP 26.0)  This option encodes \fITerm\fR in an alternative local version of the external term format. When decoded by the same runtime system instance, it produces a term identical to original term, even if the node name and/or creation of the runtime system instance have changed between encoding and decoding.

.PP
When encoding without the \fIlocal\fR option, local identifiers such as pids, ports, and references will not remain the same if node name and/or creation of the runtime system instance changed between encoding and decoding. This is because such identifiers refer to a specific node by node name and creation.

.PP
The node name and creation change when the distribution is started or stopped. The distribution starts when the runtime system is started with the \fI-name\fR or \fI-sname\fR command-line arguments. Note that the actual start of the distribution occurs after other code in the startup phase has already begun executing. The distribution can also be started by calling \fInet_kernel:start/2\fR and stopped by calling \fInet_kernel:stop/1\fR, provided it was not started via the command line.

.PP
When decoding a term encoded with the \fIlocal\fR option using, for example, \fIbinary_to_term/1\fR, the runtime system attempts to verify that the term was encoded by the same runtime system instance. In most cases, decoding will fail if it was encoded by a different instance. However, this verification is not foolproof. You \fIshould\fR ensure that terms encoded with the local option are \fIonly\fR decoded by the same Erlang runtime system instance that encoded them.

.PP
Since only the runtime system that encoded a term using the \fIlocal\fR option can decode it, the local encoding is typically pieced together with something else to produce a reply to where the local encoding originates. If a term encoded with the local option has its leading version number stripped, it can be embedded as part of a larger term (for example as an element in a tuple) when encoding in the external term format using, for example, EI.  In this case, you would strip the version number using \fIei_decode_version()\fR and append the remaining local encoding using, for example, \fIei_x_append_buf()\fR.

.PP
A common use case for the \fIlocal\fR option is when making a request from a process to a port driver driver while leveraging the selective receive optimization for handling the reply.

.PP
In this scenario:

.nr li 0 1
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
A reference is created.

.RE

.nr li 0 1
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
The reference is serialized using the external term format with the \fIlocal\fR option.

.RE

.nr li 0 1
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
This serialized reference is passed to the driver in the request.

.RE

.nr li 0 1
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\n+[li].\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "\n+[li]." 4
.\}.PP
The process then waits for a reply message in a selective receive, matching on the reference.

.RE

.PP
The driver should send the reply using either \fIerl_drv_output_term()\fR or \fIerl_drv_send_term()\fR using the term type \fIERL_DRV_EXT2TERM\fR for the reference previously received in the request.

.PP
Note that you should not strip the leading version number from the local encoding when using the term type \fIERL_DRV_EXT2TERM\fR. If the reference is not encoded with the \fIlocal\fR option, and distribution is started or stopped while the request is ongoing, the requesting process will hang indefinitely because the reference in the reply message will never match.

.PP
This option cannot be combined with the \fIdeterministic\fR option.

.PP
For more details, see \fILOCAL_EXT\fR.

.PP
See also \fIbinary_to_term/1\fR.

.RE

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> List = lists:duplicate(20, $=).
"===================="
2> term_to_binary(List, []).
<<131,107,0,20,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,61,
  61,61,61,61,61,61>>
3> term_to_binary(List, [compressed]).
<<131,80,0,0,0,23,120,156,203,102,16,177,197,2,0,61,98,5,
  68>>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBterm_to_iovec(Term) -> ext_iovec() when Term :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the encoding of \fITerm\fR according to the Erlang external term format as \fIext_iovec/0\fR.

.PP
This function produce the same encoding as \fIterm_to_binary/1\fR, but with another return type. The call \fIiolist_to_binary(term_to_iovec(Term))\fR will produce exactly the same result as the call \fIterm_to_binary(Term)\fR.

.PP
\fIterm_to_iovec/1\fR is a pure optimization of the functionality provided by \fIterm_to_binary/1\fR. For example, it can reference off-heap binaries directly instead of copying their contents into the result.

.PP
See also \fIterm_to_binary/1\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> term_to_iovec({binary:copy(~"a", 65), binary:copy(~"b", 65)}).
[<<131,104,2,109,0,0,0,65>>,
 <<"aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa">>,
 <<109,0,0,0,65>>,
 <<"bbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb">>]

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBterm_to_iovec(Term, Options) -> ext_iovec()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Term :: term(),\fR
\fB                           Options ::\fR
\fB                               [compressed |\fR
\fB                                {compressed, Level :: 0..9} |\fR
\fB                                deterministic |\fR
\fB                                {minor_version, Version :: 0..2} |\fR
\fB                                local].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the encoding of \fITerm\fR according to the Erlang external term format as \fIext_iovec/0\fR.

.PP
This function produce the same encoding as \fIterm_to_binary/2\fR, but with another return type. The call \fIiolist_to_binary(term_to_iovec(Term, Opts))\fR will produce exactly the same result as \fIterm_to_binary(Term, Opts)\fR.

.PP
This function supports all options supported by \fIterm_to_binary/2\fR.

.PP
\fIterm_to_iovec/2\fR is a pure optimization of the functionality provided by \fIterm_to_binary/2\fR. For example, it can reference off-heap binaries directly instead of copying their contents into the result.

.PP
See also \fIterm_to_binary/2\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> term_to_iovec({binary:copy(~"a", 65), binary:copy(~"b", 65)}, [deterministic]).
[<<131,104,2,109,0,0,0,65>>,
 <<"aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa">>,
 <<109,0,0,0,65>>,
 <<"bbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb">>]

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBthrow(Any) -> no_return() when Any :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Raises an exception of class \fIthrow\fR. Intended to be used to do non-local returns from functions.

.PP
If evaluated within a catch expression, the catch expression returns value \fIAny\fR.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
1> catch throw({hello, there}).
{hello,there}

.fi

.PP
If evaluated within a \fItry\fR-block of a try expression, the value \fIAny\fR can be caught within the catch block.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
1>  try
        throw({my_exception, "Something happened"})
    catch
        throw:{my_exception, Desc} ->
            io:format(standard_error, "Error: ~s~n", [Desc])
    end.
%% Output to standard error: Error: Something happened

.fi

.PP
If \fIthrow/1\fR is not evaluated within a catch, a \fInocatch\fR run-time error occurs.

.PP
See the guide about errors and error handling for additional information.


.RE
.B
\fBtime() -> Time when Time :: calendar:time().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the current time as \fI{Hour, Minute, Second}\fR.

.PP
The time zone and Daylight Saving Time correction depend on the underlying OS. The return value is based on the OS System Time.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
> time().
{9,42,44}

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtime_offset() -> integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the current time offset between Erlang monotonic time and Erlang system time in \fInative\fR time unit. Current time offset added to an Erlang monotonic time gives corresponding Erlang system time.

.PP
The time offset may or may not change during operation depending on the time warp mode used.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRA change in time offset can be observed at slightly different points in time by different processes. If the runtime system is in multi-time warp mode, the time offset is changed when the runtime system detects that the OS system time has changed. The runtime system will, however, not detect this immediately when it occurs. A task checking the time offset is scheduled to execute at least once a minute; so, under normal operation this is to be detected within a minute, but during heavy load it can take longer time.



.RE
.B
\fBtime_offset(Unit) -> integer() when Unit :: time_unit().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the current time offset between Erlang monotonic time and Erlang system time converted into the \fIUnit\fR passed as argument.

.PP
Same as calling \fIerlang:convert_time_unit\fR\fI(\fR \fIerlang:time_offset()\fR\fI, native, Unit)\fR however optimized for commonly used \fIUnit\fRs.


.RE
.B
\fBtimestamp() -> Timestamp when Timestamp :: timestamp().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns current Erlang system time on the format \fI{MegaSecs, Secs, MicroSecs}\fR.

.PP
This format is the same as \fIos:timestamp/0\fR and the deprecated \fIerlang:now/0\fR use. The reason for the existence of \fIerlang:timestamp()\fR is purely to simplify use for existing code that assumes this time stamp format. Current Erlang system time can more efficiently be retrieved in the time unit of your choice using \fIerlang:system_time/1\fR.

.PP
The \fIerlang:timestamp()\fR BIF is equivalent to:

.IP
.nf
timestamp() ->
    ErlangSystemTime = erlang:system_time(microsecond),
    MegaSecs = ErlangSystemTime div 1000_000_000_000,
    Secs = ErlangSystemTime div 1000_000 - MegaSecs*1000_000,
    MicroSecs = ErlangSystemTime rem 1000_000,
    {MegaSecs, Secs, MicroSecs}.

.fi

.PP
It, however, uses a native implementation that does not build garbage on the heap and with slightly better performance.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThis time is \fInot\fR a monotonically increasing time in the general case. For more information, see the documentation of time warp modes in the User's Guide.



.RE
.B
\fBtl(List) -> Tail\fR
\fB            when List :: nonempty_maybe_improper_list(), Tail :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the tail of \fIList\fR, which is the list without its first element.

.PP
It works with improper lists.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> tl([geesties, guilies, beasties]).
[guilies, beasties]
2> tl([geesties]).
[]
3> tl([geesties, guilies, beasties | improper_end]).
[guilies, beasties | improper_end]
4> tl([geesties | improper_end]).
improper_end
5> tl([]).
** exception error: bad argument
     in function  tl/1
        called as tl([])
        *** argument 1: not a nonempty list

.fi

.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if \fIList\fR is an empty list \fI[]\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace(PidPortSpec, How, FlagList) -> integer()\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   PidPortSpec ::\fR
\fB                       pid() |\fR
\fB                       port() |\fR
\fB                       all | processes | ports | existing |\fR
\fB                       existing_processes | existing_ports | new |\fR
\fB                       new_processes | new_ports,\fR
\fB                   How :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                   FlagList :: [trace_flag()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Turn on or off trace flags on processes or ports for the static legacy trace session.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBChange \fR

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
This function is superseded by \fItrace:process/4\fR and \fItrace:port/4\fR that

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
operate on dynamic trace sessions.

.RE

.PP
Argument \fIFlagList\fR can contain two additional options:

{tracer, Tracer}
.RS 2
Specifies where to send the trace messages. 
\fITracer\fR must be the process identifier of a local process or the port identifier of a local port.

.RE

{tracer, TracerModule, TracerState}
.RS 2
Specifies that a tracer module is to be called instead of sending a trace message. The tracer module can then ignore or change the trace message. For more details on how to write a tracer module, see 
\fIerl_tracer\fR.

.RE

.PP
If no \fItracer\fR is specified, the calling process receives all the trace messages. The legacy trace session has no specified tracer.

.PP
For further documentation see \fItrace:process/4\fR and \fItrace:port/4\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_delivered(Tracee) -> Ref\fR
\fB                         when Tracee :: pid() | all, Ref :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Calling this function makes sure all trace messages have been delivered.

.PP
The delivery of trace messages (generated by \fIerlang:trace/3\fR, \fIseq_trace\fR, or \fIerlang:system_profile/2\fR) is dislocated on the time-line compared to other events in the system. If you know that \fITracee\fR has passed some specific point in its execution, and you want to know when at least all trace messages corresponding to events up to this point have reached the tracer, use \fIerlang:trace_delivered(Tracee)\fR.

.PP
When it is guaranteed that all trace messages are delivered to the tracer up to the point that \fITracee\fR reached at the time of the call to \fIerlang:trace_delivered(Tracee)\fR, then a \fI{trace_delivered, Tracee, Ref}\fR message is sent to the caller of \fIerlang:trace_delivered(Tracee)\fR .

.PP
Notice that message \fItrace_delivered\fR does \fInot\fR imply that trace messages have been delivered. Instead it implies that all trace messages that \fIare to be delivered\fR have been delivered. It is not an error if \fITracee\fR is not, and has not been traced by someone, but if this is the case, \fIno\fR trace messages have been delivered when the \fItrace_delivered\fR message arrives.

.PP
Notice that \fITracee\fR must refer to a process currently or previously existing on the same node as the caller of \fIerlang:trace_delivered(Tracee)\fR resides on. The special \fITracee\fR atom \fIall\fR denotes all processes that currently are traced in the node.

.PP
When used together with a Tracer Module, any message sent in the trace callback is guaranteed to have reached its recipient before the \fItrace_delivered\fR message is sent.

.PP
Example: Process \fIA\fR is \fITracee\fR, port \fIB\fR is tracer, and process \fIC\fR is the port owner of \fIB\fR. \fIC\fR wants to close \fIB\fR when \fIA\fR exits. To ensure that the trace is not truncated, \fIC\fR can call \fIerlang:trace_delivered(A)\fR when \fIA\fR exits, and wait for message \fI{trace_delivered, A, Ref}\fR before closing \fIB\fR.

.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if \fITracee\fR does not refer to a process (dead or alive) on the same node as the caller of \fIerlang:trace_delivered(Tracee)\fR resides on.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_info(PidPortFuncEvent, Item) -> Res\fR
\fB                    when\fR
\fB                        PidPortFuncEvent ::\fR
\fB                            pid() |\fR
\fB                            port() |\fR
\fB                            new | new_processes | new_ports |\fR
\fB                            {Module, Function, Arity} |\fR
\fB                            on_load | send | 'receive',\fR
\fB                        Module :: module(),\fR
\fB                        Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                        Arity :: arity(),\fR
\fB                        Item ::\fR
\fB                            flags | tracer | traced | match_spec |\fR
\fB                            meta | meta_match_spec | call_count |\fR
\fB                            call_time | call_memory | all,\fR
\fB                        Res :: trace_info_return().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns trace information about a port, process, function, or event for the static legacy trace session.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBChange \fR

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
This function is superseded by \fItrace:info/3\fR that operates on dynamic trace

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
sessions.

.RE


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_pattern(MFA, MatchSpec) -> non_neg_integer()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           MFA :: trace_pattern_mfa() | send | 'receive',\fR
\fB                           MatchSpec ::\fR
\fB                               (MatchSpecList :: trace_match_spec()) |\fR
\fB                               boolean() |\fR
\fB                               restart | pause.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Equivalent to \fIerlang:trace_pattern(Event, MatchSpec, [])\fR, retained for backward compatibility.


.RE
.B
\fBtrace_pattern(send, MatchSpec, []) -> non_neg_integer()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           MatchSpec ::\fR
\fB                               (MatchSpecList :: trace_match_spec()) |\fR
\fB                               boolean();\fR
\fB                   ('receive', MatchSpec, []) -> non_neg_integer()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           MatchSpec ::\fR
\fB                               (MatchSpecList :: trace_match_spec()) |\fR
\fB                               boolean();\fR
\fB                   (MFA, MatchSpec, FlagList) -> non_neg_integer()\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           MFA :: trace_pattern_mfa(),\fR
\fB                           MatchSpec ::\fR
\fB                               (MatchSpecList :: trace_match_spec()) |\fR
\fB                               boolean() |\fR
\fB                               restart | pause,\fR
\fB                           FlagList :: [trace_pattern_flag()].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Set trace pattern for call, send and receive tracing on the static legacy trace session.

.RS 4
.PP
\fBChange \fR

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
This function is superseded by \fItrace:function/4\fR, \fItrace:send/3\fR and

.RE

.RS 4
.PP
\fItrace:recv/3\fR that operate on dynamic trace sessions.

.RE

.PP
Argument \fIFlagList\fR can contain two additional options for call tracing:

{meta, Pid} | {meta, TracerModule, TracerState}
.RS 2
Turns on or off meta-tracing for all types of function calls. Trace messages are sent to the tracer whenever any of the specified functions are called. If no tracer is specified, 
\fIself/0\fR is used as a default tracer process.

.RE

.PP
For further documentation see \fItrace:function/4\fR , \fItrace:send/3\fR and \fItrace:recv/3\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtrunc(Number) -> integer() when Number :: number().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Truncates the decimals of \fINumber\fR.

.PP
See also \fIround/1\fR, \fIfloor/1\fR, and \fIceil/1\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> trunc(5.7).
5
2> trunc(-5.7).
-5
3> trunc(5).
5
4> trunc(36028797018963969.0).
36028797018963968

.fi

.PP
In the last example, \fItrunc(36028797018963969.0)\fR evaluates to \fI36028797018963968\fR. This happens because the number \fI36028797018963969.0\fR cannot be represented exactly as a floating-point value. Instead, it is represented as \fI36028797018963968.0\fR, which is the closest representable floating-point value. See Representation of Floating Point Numbers for additional information.


.RE
.B
\fBtuple_size(Tuple) -> non_neg_integer() when Tuple :: tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the number of elements in \fITuple\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> tuple_size({a, b, c}).
3

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtuple_to_list(Tuple) -> [term()] when Tuple :: tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns a list corresponding to \fITuple\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
1> tuple_to_list({share, {'Ericsson_B', 163}}).
[share,{'Ericsson_B',163}]

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBunalias(Alias) -> boolean() when Alias :: reference().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Deactivate the alias \fIAlias\fR previously created by the calling process.

.PP
An alias can, for example, be created via \fIalias/0\fR or \fImonitor/3\fR. \fIunalias/1\fR will always deactivate the alias regardless of options used when creating the alias.

.PP
Returns true if \fIAlias\fR was a currently active alias for current processes; otherwise, false.

.PP
For more information on process aliases see the \fIProcess Aliases\fR section of the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBunique_integer() -> integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Generates and returns an integer unique on current runtime system instance.

.PP
Equivalent to calling \fIerlang:unique_integer([])\fR.

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
> erlang:unique_integer().
-576460752303422335

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBunique_integer(ModifierList) -> integer()\fR
\fB                        when\fR
\fB                            ModifierList :: [Modifier],\fR
\fB                            Modifier :: positive | monotonic.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Generates and returns an integer unique on current runtime system instance.

.PP
The integer is unique in the sense that this BIF, using the same set of modifiers, does not return the same integer more than once on the current runtime system instance. Each integer value can of course be constructed by other means.

.PP
By default, when \fI[]\fR is passed as \fIModifierList\fR, both negative and positive integers can be returned. This to use the range of integers that do not need heap memory allocation as much as possible. By default the returned integers are also only guaranteed to be unique, that is, any returned integer can be smaller or larger than previously returned integers.

.PP
\fIModifier\fRs:

positive
.RS 2
Returns only positive integers.

.PP
Notice that by passing the \fIpositive\fR modifier you will get heap allocated integers (bignums) quicker.


.RE

monotonic
.RS 2
Returns strictly monotonically increasing integers corresponding to creation time. That is, the integer returned is always larger than previously returned integers on the current runtime system instance.

.PP
These values can be used to determine order between events on the runtime system instance. That is, if both \fIX = erlang:unique_integer([monotonic])\fR and \fIY = erlang:unique_integer([monotonic])\fR are executed by different processes (or the same process) on the same runtime system instance and \fIX < Y\fR, we know that \fIX\fR was created before \fIY\fR.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRStrictly monotonically increasing values are inherently quite expensive to generate and scales poorly. This is because the values need to be synchronized between CPU cores. That is, do not pass the \fImonotonic\fR modifier unless you really need strictly monotonically increasing values.



.RE

.PP
All valid \fIModifier\fRs can be combined. Repeated (valid) \fIModifier\fRs in the \fIModifierList\fR are ignored.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe set of integers returned by \fIerlang:unique_integer/1\fR using different sets of \fIModifier\fRs \fIwill overlap\fR. For example, by calling \fIunique_integer([monotonic])\fR](\fIunique_integer/1\fR), and [\fIunique_integer([positive, monotonic])\fR repeatedly, you will eventually see some integers that are returned by both calls.


.PP
Failures:

badarg
.RS 2
if 
\fIModifierList\fR is not a proper list.

.RE

badarg
.RS 2
if 
\fIModifier\fR is not a valid modifier.

.RE

.SS "Examples"

.IP
.nf
> erlang:unique_integer([positive]).
1186

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBuniversaltime() -> DateTime when DateTime :: calendar:datetime().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the current date and time according to Universal Time Coordinated (UTC) in the form \fI{{Year, Month, Day}, {Hour, Minute, Second}}\fR if supported by the underlying OS. Otherwise \fIerlang:universaltime()\fR is equivalent to \fIerlang:localtime()\fR. The return value is based on the OS System Time.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
> erlang:universaltime().
{{1996,11,6},{14,18,43}}

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBuniversaltime_to_localtime(Universaltime) -> Localtime\fR
\fB                                    when\fR
\fB                                        Localtime :: calendar:datetime(),\fR
\fB                                        Universaltime ::\fR
\fB                                            calendar:datetime().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Converts Universal Time Coordinated (UTC) date and time to local date and time in the form \fI{{Year, Month, Day}, {Hour, Minute, Second}}\fR if supported by the underlying OS. Otherwise no conversion is done, and \fIUniversaltime\fR is returned.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
> erlang:universaltime_to_localtime({{1996,11,6},{14,18,43}}).
{{1996,11,7},{15,18,43}}

.fi

.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if \fIUniversaltime\fR denotes an invalid date and time.


.RE
.B
\fBunlink(Id) -> true when Id :: pid() | port().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Removes a link between the calling process and another process or a port identified by \fIId\fR.

.PP
We will from here on call the identified process or port unlinkee.

.PP
A link can be set up using the \fIlink/1\fR BIF. For more information on links and exit signals due to links, see the \fIProcesses\fR chapter in the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Links

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Sending Exit Signals

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Receiving Exit Signals

.RE

.PP
Once \fIunlink(Id)\fR has returned, it is guaranteed that the link between the caller and the unlinkee has no effect on the caller in the future (unless the link is setup again). Note that if the caller is trapping exits, an \fI{'EXIT', Id, ExitReason}\fR message due to the link may have been placed in the message queue of the caller before the \fIunlink(Id)\fR call completed. Also note that the \fI{'EXIT', Id, ExitReason}\fR message may be the result of the link, but may also be the result of the unlikee sending the caller an exit signal by calling the \fIexit/2\fR BIF. Therefore, it may or may not be appropriate to clean up the message queue after a call to \fIunlink(Id)\fR as follows, when trapping exits:

.IP
.nf
unlink(Id),
receive
    {'EXIT', Id, _} ->
        true
after 0 ->
        true
end

.fi

.PP
The link removal is performed asynchronously. If such a link does not exist, nothing is done. A detailed description of the link protocol can be found in the \fIDistribution Protocol\fR chapter of the \fIERTS User's Guide\fR.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRFor some important information about distributed signals, see the \fIBlocking Signaling Over Distribution\fR section in the \fIProcesses\fR chapter of the \fIErlang Reference Manual\fR.


.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if \fIId\fR does not identify a process or a node local port.


.RE
.B
\fBunregister(RegName) -> true when RegName :: atom().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Removes the \fIregistered name\fR \fIRegName\fR associated with a process identifier or a port identifier from the \fIname registry\fR.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
> unregister(db).
true

.fi

.PP
Keep in mind that you can still receive signals associated with the registered name after it has been unregistered as the sender may have looked up the name before sending to it.

.PP
Users are advised not to unregister system processes.

.PP
Failure: \fIbadarg\fR if \fIRegName\fR is not a registered name.


.RE
.B
\fBwhereis(RegName) -> pid() | port() | undefined\fR
\fB                 when RegName :: atom().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the process identifier or port identifier with the \fIregistered name\fR \fIRegName\fR from the \fIname registry\fR. Returns \fIundefined\fR if the name is not registered.

.PP
For example:

.IP
.nf
> whereis(db).
<0.43.0>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fByield() -> true.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Tries to give other processes with the same or higher priority (if any) a chance to execute before returning. There is no guarantee that any other process runs between the invocation and return of \fIerlang:yield/0\fR.

.PP
See the documentation for \fIreceive-after\fR expressions for how to make the current process sleep for a specific number of milliseconds.

.PP
\fBWARNING: \fRThere is seldom or never any need to use this BIF. Using this BIF without a thorough grasp of how the scheduler works can cause performance degradation. The current implementation of this function puts the current process last in the current scheduler's queue for processes of the same priority as the current process.



.RE
